   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="essay">
            <head>
               <bibl>
                  <author type="writer">
                     <name>
                        <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Elizabeth Inchbald</ref>
                     </name>
                  </author>
                  <title type="main" level="a">REMARKS [on <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Way
                           to Keep Him</title></hi>].<note>"Remarks." <hi rendition="#italics"
                                 ><title><title>The Way to Keep Him</title>; A Comedy, In Five Acts;
                              By <ref target="people.html#MurphyArthur">Arthur Murphy</ref>, Esq. As
                              Performed at the Theatres Royal, <ref target="people.html#DruryLane"
                                 >Drury Lane</ref> and <ref target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent
                                 Garden</ref>. Printed Under the Authority of the Managers From the
                              Prompt Book. With Remarks by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs"
                                 >Mrs. Inchbald</ref></title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman,
                        Hurst, Rees, and Orme, Paternoster Row, pp. 3-5. <hi rendition="#italics"
                              ><title level="m">The British Theatre; or, A Collection of Plays,
                              Which Are Acted At the Theatres Royal, <ref
                                 target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury Lane</ref>, <ref
                                 target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref>, and <ref
                                 target="people.html#Haymarket">Haymarket</ref>. Printed Under the
                              Authority of the Managers from the Prompt Books. With Biographical and
                              Critical Remarks, by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs.
                                 Inchbald.</ref></title></hi> In Twenty-Five Volumes. Vol. XV. <hi
                           rendition="#italics">
                           <title><ref target="people.html#BarbarossaAruj"
                           >Barbarossa</ref></title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Way to
                              Keep Him</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>All in the
                              Wrong</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Grecian
                              Daughter</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Know Your Own
                              Mind</title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees, and Orme,
                        Paternoster Row. 1808. <ref target="people.html#MurphyArthur">Murphy</ref>
                        originally produced a three-act version of this play, which was first staged
                        at the <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Theatre Royal, Drury Lane</ref>
                        on January 24<hi rendition="#sup">th</hi>, 1760. The first performance of
                        the present, five-act version of this play was staged at the <ref
                           target="people.html#DruryLane">Theatre Royal, Drury Lane</ref> on January
                           10<hi rendition="#sup">th</hi>, 1761. Laura DeWitt and Mary A. Waters
                        edited this essay for <hi rendition="#italics">The Criticism
                        Archive</hi>.</note>
                     <lb rendition="#center"/>______ </title>
               </bibl>
            </head>
            <p><ref target="people.html#ChurchillCharles">Churchill</ref>, in his admirable poem,
                  "<title>The Rosciad</title>," has said of the author of "<title>The Way to Keep
                  Him</title>"&#8212; <quote>And prudent dulness mark'd him for a mayor.<note>From
                     the fifth edition of <ref target="people.html#ChurchillCharles">Charles
                        Churchill</ref>'s <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Rosciad</title></hi>
                     (1761, p. 18).</note></quote> How little <ref target="people.html#MurphyArthur"
                  >Murphy</ref> was deserving of the imputation of dulness, this comedy can
               testify.&#8212;It is nevertheless inferior to his "<title>All in the Wrong</title>:"
               for there, events are more naturally produced, and no one character proceeds to the
               very confines of extravagance, like Sir Bashful Constant.<note><ref
                     target="people.html#MurphyArthur">Murphy</ref>'s comedy <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>All in the Wrong</title></hi> was first performed
                  on June 15<hi rendition="#sup">th</hi>, 1761. In <hi rendition="#italics"
                        ><title>The Way to Keep Him</title></hi>, much of the plot revolves around
                  Sir Bashful Constant, a man who dearly loves his wife but believes it unbecoming
                  to express it, and as such spends much of the play treating her poorly and
                  bickering with her. The characters of the Constants were new additions to the
                  five-act version of the play.</note></p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#MurphyArthur">Mr. Murphy</ref> wrote "<title>The Way to Keep
                  Him</title>" originally in three acts; then wishing to increase the number to
               five, he introduced this character of Sir Bashful.&#8212;He added to the length of
               his play, but diminished its probability. Much genius is however to be discerned in
               the conception of this part, and is, in some scenes, displayed with the happiest
               effect. In others, the husband's whimsical timidity proceeds so far, that it appears
               more like want of understanding than want of manly boldness; and when once a
               deficiency of intellects is discovered instead of a silly bias in them, all interest
               is gone for the person concerned.</p>
            <fw type="sig"><hi rendition="#smcaps">b 2</hi></fw>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>It is impossible to attend to characters destitute of sense; and delightful to
               observe particular follies, usurping the reason of those, who, in all other respects,
               are wise. Fools who accidentally have sapience, are too despicable to be
               heeded;&#8212;but the wise man, who is accidentally a fool, is an instructive picture
               of human nature, and worthy the most profound meditation.</p>

            <p>Most of the remaining characters belong to this valuable class&#8212;Lovemore and his
               wife are both depicted from nature, and their conduct to each other has an excellent
               tendency to reform the evils, and avert the ills, of the marriage state.<note>The
                  Lovemores are also additions to the five-act version of the present play. Mrs.
                  Lovemore has become dull in her marriage; as such, Mr. Lovemore pursues other
                  women. As Mr. Lovemore pursues Lady Constant, he feeds Sir Constant bad advice on
                  how to treat his wife to better his chances. By the end of the play, Mrs.
                  Lovemore's behavior has become enlivened by the shenanigans of the male
                  characters' pursuits, thereby enticing her husband once again.</note></p>

            <p>The Widow Bellmour is another well drawn personage.<note>The Widow Bellmour is the
                  first pursuit of Mr. Lovemore before he turns his attention to Lady
                  Constant.</note> She talks perfect wisdom, and all she says is perfectly with good
               intent;&#8212;but it may be apprehended that her precepts have had too much force
               with some wives of fashion, whose good humour at home, and indifference to their
               husbands' incontinence, may have betrayed them into a carelessness about their
               own.</p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#AbingtonFrances">Mrs. Abington</ref> and <ref
                  target="people.html#FarrenElizabeth">Miss Farren</ref> (the present <ref
                  target="people.html#FarrenElizabeth">Countess of Derby</ref>) were both, at the
               two different houses, and at the self same time, much admired in the Widow
                     Bellmour.<note><ref target="people.html#AbingtonFrances">Frances Abington</ref>
                  assumed the role of the Widow Bellmour at <ref target="people.html#DruryLane"
                     >Drury Lane</ref> on November 27<hi rendition="#sup">th</hi>, 1765, which she
                  performed regularly at the same theatre until 1782. <ref
                     target="people.html#FarrenElizabeth">Elizabeth Farren</ref> took up the same
                  role at <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury Lane</ref> on April 24<hi
                     rendition="#sup">th</hi>, 1781, a role she acted regularly at that theatre
                  until 1790. The two shared the role at <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury
                     Lane</ref> for roughly a year before <ref target="people.html#AbingtonFrances"
                     >Abington</ref> briefly retired the role to assume it again at <ref
                     target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref> from 1785 to 1798.</note>
               <ref target="people.html#AbingtonFrances">Mrs. Abington</ref>'s performance was the
               best,&#8212;yet not so much superior to <ref target="people.html#FarrenElizabeth"
                  >Miss Farren</ref>'s, as <ref target="people.html#FarrenElizabeth">Miss
                  Farren</ref> was superior to <ref target="people.html#AbingtonFrances">Mrs.
                  Abington</ref> in youth and personal charms.</p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#MurphyArthur">Murphy</ref> has given a fulsome dedication of
               this play to the latter actress, more disgraceful to him than <ref
                  target="people.html#ChurchillCharles">Churchill</ref>'s satire,&#8212;and not more
                     true.<note><ref target="people.html#MurphyArthur">Murphy</ref> dedicated the
                  1787 edition of this play to <ref target="people.html#AbingtonFrances"
                     >Abington</ref>, effusively praising her talent in the role of the Widow
                  Bellmour and granting her credit for the play's success.</note></p>
            <pb n="5"/>
            <p>The biographical part of that satirical poem, which applies to the author of this
               comedy, is mere fact. He was educated at St. Omer's, and though designed for a
               priest, he once attempted the profession of a player. He appeared on the stage in the
               part of <ref target="people.html#Othello">Othello</ref>; but a strong voice being
               wanted to assist his strong judgment, and grace of person to embellish its symmetry,
               he changed this pursuit to the study of the law, and became a member of the Society
               of Lincoln's Inn.<note>The preceding biographical information is indeed present in
                  the fifth edition of <ref target="people.html#ChurchillCharles">Churchill</ref>'s
                     <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Rosciad</title></hi> (1761, pp. 17-18).
                     <ref target="people.html#MurphyArthur">Murphy</ref> attended the Jesuit-run
                  College of St. Omer's in France, where he studied the classics for six years.
                  Persuaded by his friend <ref target="people.html#FooteSamuel">Samuel Foot</ref> to
                  try his hand at acting, <ref target="people.html#MurphyArthur">Murphy</ref> took
                  up the role of <ref target="people.html#Othello">Othello</ref> at <ref
                     target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref> on October 18<hi
                     rendition="#sup">th</hi>, 1754. Although he was successful in the role, he only
                  continued his acting career for two seasons, as his interests drew him to the law.
                  In 1757, he was accepted into The Honourable Society of Lincoln's Inn, one of the
                  four professional associations for barristers in England and Wales. <ref
                     target="people.html#MurphyArthur">Murphy</ref> was then admitted to the bar in
                  1762 and practiced law until 1788, which greatly limited the amount of time he
                  could invest in his writing.</note> Still, he attached himself to his beloved
               theatre by the ties of an author; and passed his happiest hours with <ref
                  target="people.html#GarrickDavid">Garrick</ref>, <ref
                  target="people.html#FooteSamuel">Foote</ref>, <ref
                  target="people.html#JohnsonSamuel">Dr. Johnson</ref>, and other men of wit and
                     imagination.<note><ref target="people.html#MurphyArthur">Murphy</ref> held
                  close friendships with the above three men, frequently collaborating with <ref
                     target="people.html#GarrickDavid">Garrick</ref> and <ref
                     target="people.html#FooteSamuel">Foote</ref> and eventually writing biographies
                  for <ref target="people.html#GarrickDavid">Garrick</ref> and <ref
                     target="people.html#JohnsonSamuel">Johnson</ref>.</note></p>

            <p>It had perhaps been happy for <ref target="people.html#MurphyArthur">Murphy</ref>,
               had the reproach of dulness, which <ref target="people.html#ChurchillCharles"
                  >Churchill</ref> has cast upon him, been just; for could it have conferred upon
               him the mayoralty of the city of London, no doubt it would have been a fortunate
               exchange for that poetic genius which he possessed; and which would not have secured
               to him in old age a mere existence, but for its claims upon the taste and pity of his
               Sovereign.</p>

            <p><ref target="people.html#MurphyArthur">Murphy</ref> died in the summer of 1805, a
               pensioner on the king's private purse:<note><ref target="people.html#MurphyArthur"
                     >Murphy</ref> died in his London residence on June 18<hi rendition="#sup"
                     >th</hi>, 1805. Despite the income he received from his writings, <ref
                     target="people.html#MurphyArthur">Murphy</ref> struggled with his finances due
                  to various debts, and beginning in 1798, <ref
                     target="people.html#GeorgeIIIKingofGreatBritain">King George III</ref> had
                  granted him a pension of £200 per year.</note> as related in the Remarks on his
               comedy of "<title>All in the Wrong</title>."</p>
            <fw type="sig"><hi rendition="#smcaps">b 3</hi></fw>
         </div>
